						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bellum wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Hmm, not sure what segment does at all, actually.  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /></div><br />Please see <a href="http://www.cc65.org/doc/ca65-11.html#ss11.87" class="postlink">segments</a> in ca65 Users Guide. If you don't understand something in that section, please ask.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I understand what say_hello does, but I don't understand why you store the numbers $21 and $CA in memory.</div><br />That's something you'll learn more about once you start to learn about the PPU. For now, suffice it to say that VRAM addresses are formed $2000 + $20*y + x, and $21CA represents (x=10, y=14).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">So, for instance, I could say...<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">astring&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;.byt &quot;This is a string!&quot;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LDA astring,0&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;;loads astring&#91;0&#93; into a</div></div>
<br />No, that's a syntax error. You must use comma only for index registers (e.g. astring,x or astring,y); you can use + for constant offsets from the start of an array (e.g. astring+0 or astring+3).
<br />
<br />
<br />thefox: In which version of ca65 was .charmap introduced?</div>

